# Lens Studio {{VERSION}} Project Reference

{{PLATFORM_LINE}}This project uses Lens Studio. Scripts can be written in JavaScript (ES2021 compliant) or TypeScript.

Important Notes:

- The global execution context is the `script` object in JavaScript, or `this` in TypeScript components.
- UI inputs are defined using comment-based decorators (`// @input`) in JavaScript, or `@input` decorators in TypeScript.
- Do not use `window` or `document` objects; this is a unique runtime, not a browser.
- All components must extend `BaseScriptComponent` in TypeScript.
- Lens Studio uses a **right-handed coordinate system**: +X is right, +Y is up, -Z is forward.
- World units are in **centimeters** (cm) and **degrees** (however, many APIs operate in radians).
- Always work with files inside the `Assets/` directory — this is where all project resources live.
- Never modify files in the `Cache/` directory — it contains auto-generated/cached data that is regenerated by Lens Studio.
- The **Lens API** (StudioLib) and the **Editor API** (editor.d.ts) are two completely separate APIs for different purposes. The **Lens API** is the language for building AR experiences — use it for all lens project scripts (TypeScript or JavaScript). The **Editor API** is only for controlling the Lens Studio application itself — use it only when you need to interact with the app (e.g., modify settings, perform app actions). Editor API scripts must be written in **JavaScript only**.

## Subagents & Skills

**Before performing any action, check for available subagents and skills.** Specialized subagents and skills are located at `.claude/agents/` and `.claude/skills/` — always inspect these directories to see what's available. Use subagents via the Task tool and skills via the Skill tool.

### editor-api-agent (subagent) — REQUIRED for ALL Editor API work

**The main agent must NEVER write, draft, or reason about Editor API code.** The `editor-api-agent` subagent owns the entire Editor API lifecycle — API lookup, code writing, execution, and error handling. It carries the `editor-api-execute` skill with Editor API patterns, gotchas, and type lookup workflows that the main agent does not have access to.

When any part of a task involves the Editor API:
1. **Describe the intent** — tell the subagent *what* you need done, not *how* to do it
2. **Delegate via Task tool** — the subagent will look up the API, write correct code, execute it, and report results
3. **Never pre-write code** — do not draft Editor API snippets, reference `editor.d.ts` for code writing, or use `ExecuteEditorCode` directly

This includes: reading/writing scene properties, traversing the scene graph, accessing `LensStudio:*` modules (FileSystem, Shell, Network, etc.), bulk mutations, and any operation involving `pluginSystem`.

### Discovering new subagents and skills

Subagents and skills may be added over time. Always run a quick check:
- `ls .claude/agents/` — available subagents (delegate via Task tool)
- `ls .claude/skills/` — available skills (invoke via Skill tool if `user-invocable: true`, otherwise auto-loaded by subagents)

## Documentation

- [Lens API Reference](Support/{{STUDIOLIB_PATH}}): TypeScript definitions for the **Lens scripting API** — the language for building AR experiences. Use this for all lens project scripts (TypeScript or JavaScript).
- [Editor API Reference](Support/editor.d.ts): TypeScript definitions for the **Lens Studio Editor API** — for controlling the Lens Studio application itself (performing actions, modifying settings, checking statuses). Only use this when you need to interact with the Lens Studio app, not for building lenses.**
- [Scripting Guide](.claude/docs/scripting_guide.md): Core syntax for Inputs, Events, and exposing APIs between scripts.
- [Common API Cheatsheet](.claude/docs/api_cheatsheet.md): Essential classes for manipulating Transforms, SceneObjects, and Components.
- [Project Structure](.claude/docs/structure.md): How Lens Studio projects organize resources and objects.

## Optional

